+### 3.83 FR-E83: Run Journal Doctor (`runs doctor`)
+
+- **Description:** `flowai-workflow runs doctor --workflow <dir> --run
+  <run-id>` diagnoses one run's durability artifacts and reports EVERY
+  problem found, grouped by severity (ERROR / WARNING / OK summary; exit 0
+  when no ERRORs, 1 otherwise). Three ordered passes:
+  1. **Journal integrity** (lexical scan, no state reconstruction): file
+     exists; every line parses as JSON — a truncated FINAL line (no trailing
+     newline) is a WARNING (the expected crash artifact the writer already
+     tolerates), a non-final unparsable line is an ERROR; unknown event
+     `kind` is an ERROR; non-monotonic `seq` is an ERROR; duplicate
+     `event_id` is a WARNING (the replayer dedupes them).
+  2. **Replay invariants:** the journal is replayed via the EXISTING
+     replayer (`src/state/run-journal.ts::replayRunJournal` — single source
+     of replay truth; doctor only orchestrates and inspects the result).
+     Reported field-by-field: events after a terminal run event
+     (`run_completed`/`run_failed`/`run_aborted`); node lifecycle events for
+     undeclared nodes; `attempt_completed` without a matching
+     `attempt_started`; replayed `total_cost_usd` diverging from the sum of
+     per-node `cost_usd` lifecycle metadata (the independent per-node
+     evidence — the replayed total derives from node snapshots, so
+     metadata/snapshot drift means tampering or an engine bug).
+  3. **Filesystem cross-check:** node directories on disk under the run dir
+     that no journal event mentions (orphans — WARNING; `logs/`,
+     `worktree/`, `.hitl-inbox/` are engine infra, exempt); directories the
+     journal declares that are missing on disk (ERROR — the engine mkdirs
+     all node dirs eagerly at bootstrap, so absence is tampering, not a
+     crash artifact); a `runs/.lock` referencing this run whose recorded
+     process is dead (stale lock — WARNING).
+
+  `--repair` applies ONLY safe mechanical fixes, each reported: torn final
+  journal line (backup as `journal.jsonl.bak`, then atomic rewrite without
+  the torn line via tmp + rename) and stale-lock removal. Refusals (clear
+  error, nothing modified): the run is currently active (lock held by a
+  live process), or the journal has errors beyond the torn final line —
+  doctor never guesses at semantic repairs. `--json` emits the
+  machine-readable findings list (severity, code, message, evidence path).
+  One `--run` per invocation; flags only; no compaction.
+- **Tasks:** [runs-doctor](../tasks/2026/06/runs-doctor.md)
+- **Motivation:** `journal.jsonl` is a run's only durable record (FR-E69).
+  Crashes, manual tampering, and engine bugs can degrade it or the
+  surrounding run directory; without a doctor the operator must hand-read
+  the journal, and the only torn-line healing is the silent truncation in
+  `RunJournalWriter.open`.
+- **Acceptance criteria:**
+  - **Tests:** `src/state/doctor_test.ts` (FR-E83; fabricated run dirs:
+    clean run exit 0; torn last line WARNING; mid-file garbage ERROR;
+    unknown kind; non-monotonic seq; duplicate event_id; events after
+    terminal; undeclared node; unmatched attempt; cost-sum divergence;
+    orphan / missing / phase-nested dirs; stale lock; `--repair` torn-line
+    round-trip with byte-identical `.bak`; repair refusals on live lock and
+    mid-file garbage; `--json` shape), `src/cli_test.ts` (FR-E83;
+    `parseDoctorArgs` + `--help` listing).
+  - [x] `runs doctor` subcommand appears in CLI `--help`; argument parsing
+    follows the existing `src/cli.ts` style; no new dependencies.
+    Evidence: `cli.ts::parseDoctorArgs`, `cli.ts::printUsage`,
+    `deno task check`.
+
